Introduction


In this pratical you will be helping the smurfs handling their ever growing village. From new services like a library to new houses, even their family tree, they will need your help.
To help them, you will have to use certain aspect of Object Oriented Programming like: interface, abstract classes, overloading, subtyping, composition and inheritance to name a few.
You could use magic, however Papa Smurf might not like it. Especially after the Clumsy Smurf incident.

Knowledge is power! Brainy Smurf surely won't deny it. As a matter of fact, he happens to be in need of your help. The new Grand Smurf Library just opened and yet everything is in shambles inside, no one knows who took what and when. Brainy Smurf needs you to implement his new system to stop all this madness.
This might stop Lazy Smurf from hoarding all those books he never planned to read anyway.

Information
Here is the procedure when a villager rent an item:

We call RentItem() from Library with the villager, the item's ID, and the number of days the villager wants to have the item. library.RentItem() calls Rent() from BookRentable or DiscRentable with the villager. Initially, the item is in the librarian's inventory, and its owner is the librarian.
xRentable.Rent() calls librarian.RentItem(), which removes the item from the librarian's inventory. The librarian's inventory no longer contains the item, but the owner is still the librarian.
xRentable.Rent() changes the owner of the item so that the owner is now the villager. The villager's inventory does not yet contain the item, but the owner is the villager.
xRentable.Rent() calls villager.RentItem(), which adds the item to the villager's inventory. In the end, the item is in the villager's inventory, and its owner is the villager.

Conversely, here is the procedure when a villager returns an item to the librarian:

We call Return() from BookRentable or DiscRentable with the librarian. Initially, the item is in the villager's inventory, and its owner is the villager.
xRentable.Return() calls villager.ReturnItem(), which removes the item from the villager's inventory. The villager's inventory no longer contains the item, but the owner is still the villager.
xRentable.Return() changes the owner of the item so that the owner is now the librarian. The librarian's inventory does not yet contain the item, but the owner is the librarian.
xRentable.Return() calls librarian.ReturnItem(), which adds the item to the librarian's inventory. In the end, the item is in the librarian's inventory, and its owner is the librarian.

Fundamentals/Smurf.cs


This class represent a Smurf.

Prototype(s)
public abstract class Smurf { }

A smurf is characterized by his name and the list of rentable items he has.

  • a public string Name, the name of the smurf, with a getter only.
  • a public List<IRentableItem> Items, the list of rentable items that the smurf has, with a getter only.

You must create a constructor for the Smurf class which takes a name and initialize the Items field.

Prototype(s)
protected Smurf(string name) { }

Warning(s)
The Smurf class is abstract and its constructor is protected. You can remove the abstract keyword and change the protected to public to test it but don't forget to put it back!

Code example(s)
Smurf smurf1 = new Smurf("PapaSmurf");
// smurf1.Name = "PapaSmurf"
// smurf1.Items = {}

For now, you only need to declare those methods, you will implement them in the classes inheriting from Smurf class.

Prototype(s)
public abstract bool RentItem(IRentableItem item);

Prototype(s)
public abstract bool ReturnItem(IRentableItem item);

This method takes as parameter the Id of a rentable item and returns true if this item is in the smurf Items, false otherwise.

Prototype(s)

Warning(s)
You will need to implement the rentable items before you can test this method.

This method takes a rentable item that the villager wants to rent. It returns true if he is able to rent it, false otherwise. This method also add the rentable item to the Items of the villager if he is able to rent it.
A villager can rent a rentable item if he is the current owner of the item but the item was not in his Items when the method was called. This method will be called by Rent() of BookRentable or DiscRentable class which has already change the Owner.

Fundamentals/Item.cs


A class representing an item.

Prototype(s)
public abstract class Item { }

The only properties that all items have in common are their name and their release date.

  • a public string Name, the name of the item, with a getter only.
  • a public string ReleaseDate, the release date of the item, with a getter only.

You need to create two constructors for the Item class. The first one create an item with a name and a release date and the second one create an item with the same properties as another item.

Information
The second constructor is called a copy constructor. It allows creating a new object with identical characteristics to those of the object passed as a parameter.

Prototype(s)
protected Item(string name, string releaseDate) { }
protected Item(Item item) { }

Warning(s)
The Item class is abstract and its constructors are protected. You can remove the abstract keyword and change the protected to public to test it but don't forget to put it back!

Code example(s)
Item item1 = new Item("First item", "1st January 2001");

// item1.Name = "First item"
// item1.ReleaseDate = "1st January 2001"

Item item2 = new Item(item1);

// item2.Name = "First item"
// item2.ReleaseDate = "1st January 2001"

Console.WriteLine(item1 == item2); // false
Console.WriteLine(item1.Name == item2.Name); // true
Console.WriteLine(item1.ReleaseDate == item2.ReleaseDate); // true

Output
False
True
True

This method must return a string containing the name of the item followed by ", released on " followed by the release date.

Prototype(s)

Code example(s)
// item1.Name = "First item"
// item1.ReleaseDate = "1st January 2001"

Fundamentals/Book.cs


A class representing a book. This class inherits from Item.

Prototype(s)
public class Book { }

This class has four new properties.

  • a public string Author, the name of the author of the book, with a getter only.
  • a public uint NbPages, the number of pages of the book, with a getter only.
  • a public uint NbChapters, the number of chapters of the book, with a getter only.
  • a public uint VolumeNumber, the volume number of the book, with a getter only.

You need to create two constructor for the Book class. The first one create a book with a name, a release date, an author, a number of pages, a number of chapters and a volume number. The second one create a book with the same properties as another book.
If the number of pages, the number of chapters or the volume number is equal to 0, you must throw an ArgumentException.

Warning(s)
You must use the base keyword to initialize the parent class fields.

Prototype(s)

This method must return a string containing the item summary, followed by ", written by ", then the author, ", consisting of " and the number of pages followed by " page, organized in ", the number of chapters, " chapter, which is the ", the volume number and " volume.".
You must add a "s" after "page" if the number of pages is greater than 1 and a "s" after "chapter" if the number of chapters is greater than 1. The volume number must be immediately followed by "st", "nd", "rd" or "th" depending on its value:

  • If the units digit is 1 and the tens digit is not 1 -> "st"
  • If the units digit is 2 and the tens digit is not 1 -> "nd"
  • If the units digit is 3 and the tens digit is not 1 -> "rd"
  • Otherwise -> "th"

True
True

This operator overloading create a new disc which is the result of two others.
The resulting disc name is the name of the first one, followed by ", " and the name of the second one.
Its date is the current date in the format "yyyy-mm-dd".
The duration is the addition of the durations of the two discs.
The two discs must have the same genre, which is the one of the resulting disc. Otherwise, the operator throw an ArgumentException.

Prototype(s)
public static Disc operator +(Disc disc1, Disc disc2) { }

Hint(s)
You can get the current date with DateTime.Now. You should also format the date.

Code example(s)
Disc disc1 = new Disc("First disc", "1st January 2001", 612, "techno");
Disc disc2 = new Disc("Second disc", "2nd January 2002", 378, "techno");
Disc disc3 = new Disc("Third disc", "3rd January 2003", 450, "metal");

Disc disc4 = disc1 + disc2;
Disc disc5 = disc1 + disc3; // ArgumentException

// disc4.Name = "First disc, Second disc"
// disc4.ReleaseDate = "2024-02-26"
// disc4.Duration = 990
// disc4.Genre = "techno"

This method must return a string containing the item summary, followed by ", lasting " the duration, " and belonging to the ", the genre and " genre.".
The duration must be in the format given below, with x, the number of hours, y, the number of minutes and z, the number of seconds:

  • x hour, y minute and z second
  • x hour and y minute
  • x hour and z second
  • x hour
  • y minute and z second
  • y minute
  • z second

You must also add an "s" at the end of "hour" if x is greater than 1, an "s" at the end of "minute" if y is greater than 1 and an "s" at the end of "second" if z is greater than 1.

Warning(s)
You must use the base keyword to generate the part of the summary containing the name and the release date of the disc.

This method return the location of the new item with the name name. You must use our version of the PJW hash function to find the location. The shelfId is the 32 highest bits cast to a uint and the position is the 32 lowest bits cast to a uint.
The algorithm of our version of PJW hash function is the following:

Code example(s)
ulong h := 0
bitsSize := ulong size in bits
for i := 0 to len(name) - 1 do
  h := h << bitsSize/8 + name[i]
  ulong high := get the bitsSize/8 highest bits of h
  if high != 0 then
    h := h xor (high >> bitsSize * 7/8)
  h := h & ~high
return h

Prototype(s)

Code example(s)

This method takes an Item to add to the library, the maximum number of day the new item can be rented and the librarian who will be in charge of the new item. It returns the new RentableInfo created.

Enhancements/Recipe.cs


This class represents a recipe to craft items. The recipe indicates the list of ingredients and the result.

Prototype(s)
public class Recipe { }

A Recipe has two properties:

  • a public List<ItemSet> Ingredients, the list of all ItemSet consumed by the recipe, with a getter only.
  • a public ItemSet Result, the ItemSet produced by the recipe, with a getter only.

The recipe class has two constructors. The first uses a list of ItemSet for the ingredients and an ItemSet for the product. The second uses a string in the following format "<quantity>x<itemType> = <quantity>x<itemType> + <quantity>x<itemType> + ...". The left part represents the resulting ItemSet product and the right part represents the needed ingredients.
We assume that the type and the quantity in the string are valid. The string format will also always be valid.

Prototype(s)
public Recipe(List<ItemSet> ingredients, ItemSet result) { }
public Recipe(string info) { }

Code example(s)
List<ItemSet> ingredients1 = new List<ItemSet>();
ingredients1.Add(new ItemSet(ItemType.Bricks, 10));
ingredients1.Add(new ItemSet(ItemType.Glass, 2));

// ingredients1.Count = 2
// ingredients1[0].Type = Bricks
// ingredients1[0].Quantity = 10
// ingredients1[1].Type = Glass
// ingredients1[1].Quantity = 2

ItemSet result1 = new ItemSet(ItemType.Wall, 3);

// result1.Type = Wall
// result1.Quantity = 3

Recipe recipe1 = new Recipe(ingredients1, result1);

// recipe1.Ingredients.Count = 2
// recipe1.Ingredients[0].Type = Bricks
// recipe1.Ingredients[0].Quantity = 10
// recipe1.Ingredients[1].Type = Glass
// recipe1.Ingredients[1].Quantity = 2
// recipe1.Result.Type = Wall
// recipe1.Result.Quantity = 3

Recipe recipe2 = new Recipe("2xHouse = 16xRoof + 9xWall + 25xFloor");

// recipe2.Ingredients.Count = 3
// recipe2.Ingredients[0].Type = Roof
// recipe2.Ingredients[0].Quantity = 16
// recipe2.Ingredients[1].Type = Wall
// recipe2.Ingredients[1].Quantity = 9
// recipe2.Ingredients[2].Type = Floor
// recipe2.Ingredients[2].Quantity = 25
// recipe2.Result.Type = House
// recipe2.Result.Quantity = 2

Everyone knows that baby Smurfs are brought by storks on a blue full moon. With all these new houses and Smurfs living inside, Papa Smurf needs help. Each baby Smurf is taken care of by a "parent", an adult Smurf. From this perspective one could create a form of family tree, and that is exactly what Papa Smurf needs. However taking care of this many Smurfs in the village is proving to be quite the task for him. (Clumsy Smurf nearly burn 2 houses and the library this very morning)
Help him with this task and maybe, just maybe, he might teach you some of his magic and allow you to use it! If you don't do anything stupid with it of course.

Proficiencies/Serializer.cs


This class is a tool used to serialize and deserialize objects implementing ISerializable.

Prototype(s)
public class Serializer { }

The Serializer class has one property:

  • a public OrderedDictionary Fields, the ordered dictionary in which will be stored pairs of strings conaining the name of a field as key and the value of this field as value, with a getter only.

Information
An OrderedDictionary represents a collection of key/value pairs that are accessible by the key or index. The index is assigned based on the order in which the elements were added.

This method return a list of index of semicolons separating pairs of key and value not in more than one curled bracket.

Prototype(s)
public static List<int> FindSemicolons(string data) { }

Code example(s)
List<int> semiIndex1 = Serializer.FindSemicolons("{name:\"PoetSmurf\";age:23;friend:{name:\"SculptorSmurf\";age:25}}"); // semiIndex1 = {17, 24}
List<int> semiIndex2 = Serializer.FindSemicolons("{name:\"SculptorSmurf\";age:25}"); // semiIndex2 = {21}
List<int> semiIndex3 = Serializer.FindSemicolons("{name:\"PoetSmurf\";age:23;job:\"poet\";friendName:\"SculptorSmurf\"}"); // semiIndex3 = {17, 24, 35}

You must create two constructors for the Serializer class.
The first one does not take any parameter. The second one takes a string containing a list of "key:value" separated by ";" and surrounded by "{" and "}" where value could also be in this format.

Prototype(s)
public Serializer() { }
public Serializer(string data) { }

Code example(s)
Serializer serializer = new Serializer();

// serializer.Fields = {}

Serializer serializer = new Serializer("{name:\"PoetSmurf\";age:23;friend:{name:\"SculptorSmurf\";age:25}}");

// serializer.Fields = { "name":"\"PoetSmurf\"" ; "age":"23" ; "friend":"{name:\"Sculptor\";age:25}" }

This method add the value to the dictionary Fields with name as key. The value can be of type string, uint or ISerializable. If the type of value does not match any of these three, you must throw an FormatException.

Prototype(s)
public void AddField(string name, object value) { }

Code example(s)
Serializer serializer = new Serializer();

// serializer.Fields = {}

serializer.AddField("name", "PoetSmurf");

// serializer.Fields = { "name":"\"PoetSmurf\"" }

serializer.AddField("age", 23u);

// serializer.Fields = { "name":"\"PoetSmurf\"" ; "age":"23" }

serializer.AddField("job", "poet");

// serializer.Fields = { "name":"\"PoetSmurf\"" ; "age":"23" ; "job":"\"poet\"" }

This method convert the Fields in the following format: a list of "key:value" separated by ";" and surrounded by "{" and "}".
If the value is a string, it must be surrounded by '"'. If the value is an ISerializable, it must be in his serialized format.

Prototype(s)
public override string ToString() { }

Code example(s)
Serializer serializer = new Serializer();
serializer.AddField("name", "PoetSmurf");
serializer.AddField("age", 23u);
serializer.AddField("job", "poet");

// serializer.Fields = { "name":"\"PoetSmurf\"" ; "age":"23" ; "job":"\"poet\"" }

Console.WriteLine(serializer.ToString());

Output
{name:"PoetSmurf";age:23;job:"poet"}

This method return the value as string associated with the key name. If name is not a key of Fields, throw an ArgumentException.
A value in Fields which is a string starts and ends with '"'. They should not be present in the returned string.

Prototype(s)
public string GetFieldString(string name) { }

Code example(s)
Serializer serializer = new Serializer();
serializer.AddField("name", "PoetSmurf");
serializer.AddField("age", 23u);
serializer.AddField("job", "poet");

// serializer.Fields = { "name":"\"PoetSmurf\"" ; "age":"23" ; "job":"\"poet\"" }

Console.WriteLine(serializer.GetFieldString("name"));
serializer.GetFieldString("surname"); // ArgumentException

Output
PoetSmurf

This method return the value as uint associated with the key name. If name is not a key of Fields, throw an ArgumentException.

Adult adult1 = Adult.DeserializeAdult("{type:\"Adult\";name:\"WildSmurf\";age:23;occupation:\"Explorer\";experience:5}");

// adult1.Name = "WildSmurf"
// adult1.Age = 23
// adult1.Occupation = "Explorer"
// adult1.Experience = 5


Proficiencies/Elder.cs


This class represents an elder, which inherits from SmurfIndividual.

Prototype(s)
public class Elder { }

An elder is a SmurfIndividual with a hobby. This class has one new property:

  • a public string Hobby, the hobby of the elder, with a getter only.

You must create a constructor for the Elder class which takes a name, an age and a hobby. If the name or the hobby contains one of these characters: '{', '}', ':' or ';' , you must throw an ArgumentException.

Warning(s)
You must use the base keyword to initialize the parent class fields.

Prototype(s)
public Elder(string name, uint age, string hobby) { }

Code example(s)
Elder elder1 = new Elder("GrandpaSmurf", 102, "TellingStories");

// elder1.Name = "Grandpa Smurf"
// elder1.Age = 102
// elder1.Hobby = "TellingStories"

This method return a string in the format "{type:\"Elder\";name:<name>;age:<age>;hobby:<hobby>}" where "<name>", "<age>" and "<hobby>" are replaced by the value of their respective field.

Hint(s)
The Serializer class could be usefull.

Prototype(s)
public override string Serialize() { }

Code example(s)
Elder elder1 = new Elder("GrandpaSmurf", 102, "TellingStories");
Console.WriteLine(elder1.Serialize());

Output
{type:"Elder";name:"GrandpaSmurf";age:102;hobby:"TellingStories"}

This method takes a string in the same format than the one returned by Serialize() : "{type:\"Elder\";name:<name>;age:<age>;hobby:<hobby>}" and return an instance of the Elder class with all its fields initialized to their value in the string passed in parameters.

Hint(s)
The Serializer class could be usefull.

Prototype(s)
public static Elder DeserializeElder(string data) { }

Code example(s)

// elder1.Name = "Grandpa Smurf"

// elder1.Hobby = "TellingStories"

Proficiencies/Tree.cs


This class represents a family tree. The parent in the tree is the Smurf who takes care of the Smurfs in the two children when they were babies. This class implements ISerializable.

Prototype(s)
public class Tree { }

A tree has three properties: the smurf in the root node and two trees: the left and right children of the root node.

  • a public SmurfIndividual SmurfIndividual, the smurf who is the root node of the tree, with a getter and a private setter.
  • a public Tree? FirstChild, the first child of the tree node, with a getter and a private setter.
  • a public Tree? SecondChild, the second child of the tree node, with a getter and a private setter.

You must create three constructors for the Tree class. One for Smurfs who takes care of two baby Smurf, another one for Smurfs who takes care of one baby Smurf and the last for Smurfs who doesn't takes care of any baby Smurf.
In our Tree class, if a tree have a SecondChild not null, the FirstChild cannot be null.

Warning(s)
You must use the this keyword for the second and third constructors.

Prototype(s)
public Tree(SmurfIndividual smurfIndividual) { }
public Tree(SmurfIndividual smurfIndividual, Tree firstChild) { }
public Tree(SmurfIndividual smurfIndividual, Tree firstChild, Tree secondChild) { }

Code example(s)
Elder elder1 = new Elder("Grandpa Smurf", 102, "Telling stories");
Adult adult1 = new Adult("WildSmurf", 23, "Explorer", 5);

Tree tree2 = new Tree(adult1);

// tree2.SmurfIndividual = adult1
// tree2.FirstChild = null
// tree2.SecondChild = null

Tree tree1 = new Tree(elder1, tree2);

// tree1.SmurfIndividual = elder1
// tree1.FirstChild = tree2
// tree1.SecondChild = null

This method returns a string in one of the following formats:

  • if FirstChild and SecondChild are null -> "{smurfIndividual:<smurfIndividual>}"
  • if only SecondChild is null -> "{smurfIndividual:<smurfIndividual>;firstChild:<firstChild>}"
  • if FirstChild and SecondChild are not null -> "{smurfIndividual:<smurfIndividual>;firstChild:<firstChild>;secondChild:<secondChild>}"

In these formats, "<smurfIndividual>" needs to be replace by the serialization of SmurfIndividual, "<firstChild>", by the serialization of FirstChild and "<secondChild>", by the serialization of SecondChild.

Hint(s)
The Serializer class could be usefull.

Prototype(s)
public string Serialize() { }

Code example(s)
Elder elder1 = new Elder("Grandpa Smurf", 102, "Telling stories");
Adult adult1 = new Adult("WildSmurf", 23, "Explorer", 5);
Adult adult2 = new Adult("TrackerSmurf", 27, "Tracker", 13);
Kid kid1 = new Kid("DreamySmurf", 7, 68, 5);
Tree tree = new Tree(elder1, new Tree(adult1, new Tree(kid1)), new Tree(adult2));

// tree.SmurfIndividual = elder1
// tree.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual = adult1
// tree.FirstChild.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual = kid1
// tree.FirstChild.FirstChild.FirstChild = null
// tree.FirstChild.FirstChild.SecondChild = null
// tree.FirstChild.SecondChild = null
// tree.SecondChild.SmurfIndividual = adult2
// tree.SecondChild.FirstChild = null
// tree.SecondChild.SecondChild = null

Console.Writeline(tree.Serialize());

Output
{smurfIndividual:{type:"Elder";name:"GrandpaSmurf";age:102;hobby:"TellingStories"};firstChild:{smurfIndividual:{type:"Adult";name:"WildSmurf";age:23;occupation:"Explorer";experience:5};firstChild:{smurfIndividual:{type:"Kid";name:"DreamySmurf";age:7;height:68;grade:5}}};secondChild:{smurfIndividual:{type:"Adult";name:"TrackerSmurf";age:27;occupation:"Tracker";experience:13}}}

This method takes a string in the same format than the one returned by Serialize() just above. This method returns a new tree corresponding to the string.

Hint(s)
The Serializer class could be usefull.

Prototype(s)
public static ISerializable Deserialize(string data) { }

Code example(s)

// tree.SmurfIndividual.Name = "GrandpaSmurf"
// tree.SmurfIndividual.Age = 102
// tree.SmurfIndividual.Hobby = "TellingStories"
// tree.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual.Name = "WildSmurf"
// tree.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual.Age = 23
// tree.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual.Occupation = Explorer
// tree.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual.Experience = 5
// tree.FirstChild.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual.Name = "DreamySmurf"
// tree.FirstChild.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual.Age = 7
// tree.FirstChild.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual.Height = 68
// tree.FirstChild.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual.Grade = 5
// tree.FirstChild.FirstChild.FirstChild = null
// tree.FirstChild.FirstChild.SecondChild = null

// tree.SecondChild.SmurfIndividual.Name = "TrackerSmurf"

This method returns the number of nodes in the tree.

The number of nodes in a binary tree is 1, plus the number of nodes in the left child, plus the number of nodes in the right child. If a tree is null, its size is 0.

public int Size() { }

This method returns a Tree, which is a deep copy of the current Tree.

Hint(s)
To do a deep copy, you need to create a new tree with the same SmurfIndividual but with his FirstChild and SecondChild who are themselves deep copies of the originals.

Prototype(s)
public Tree DeepCopy() { }

Code example(s)
Elder elder1 = new Elder("Grandpa Smurf", 102, "Telling stories");
Adult adult1 = new Adult("WildSmurf", 23, "Explorer", 5);
Tree tree = new Tree(elder1, new Tree(adult1));

// tree.SmurfIndividual = elder1
// tree.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual = adult1
// tree.FirstChild.FirstChild = null
// tree.FirstChild.SecondChild = null
// tree.SecondChild = null

Tree treeB = tree.DeepCopy();

// treeB.SmurfIndividual = elder1
// treeB.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual = adult1
// treeB.FirstChild.FirstChild = null
// treeB.FirstChild.SecondChild = null
// treeB.SecondChild = null

console.WriteLine(tree == treeB); // false
console.WriteLine(tree.SmurfIndividual == treeB.SmurfIndividual); // true
console.WriteLine(tree.FirstChild == treeB.FirstChild); // false
console.WriteLine(tree.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual == treeB.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual); // true

Output
False
True
False
True

This method replace the SmurfIndividual in the root of the tree by the oldest SmurfIndividual of its two children. If the root don't have any child, the root cannot be replace and this method returns null, otherwise, it returns the tree with the SmurfIndividual in the root updated. This method is recursive and call herself on the child from which comes the new SmurfIndividual of the root.
This method will be called only on Tree where the SmurfIndividual in every node is older than the SmurfIndividuals in the two children of this node.

Information
A binary tree in which every node is greater than its child is called a max heap. One in which every node is lesser than its child is called a min heap. Here, we use a max heap where the value of nodes are the age of the smurf.

Prototype(s)
public Tree? PopOldest() { }

Code example(s)
Elder elder1 = new Elder("Grandpa Smurf", 102, "Telling stories");
Adult adult1 = new Adult("WildSmurf", 23, "Explorer", 5);
Adult adult2 = new Adult("TrackerSmurf", 27, "Tracker", 13);
Kid kid1 = new Kid("DreamySmurf", 7, 68, 5);
Tree tree1 = new Tree(elder1, new Tree(adult1, new Tree(kid1)), new Tree(adult2));

// tree1.SmurfIndividual = elder1
// tree1.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual = adult1
// tree1.FirstChild.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual = kid1
// tree1.FirstChild.FirstChild.FirstChild = null
// tree1.FirstChild.FirstChild.SecondChild = null
// tree1.FirstChild.SecondChild = null
// tree1.SecondChild.SmurfIndividual = adult2
// tree1.SecondChild.FirstChild = null
// tree1.SecondChild.SecondChild = null

Tree tree2 = tree1.PopOldest();

// tree2.SmurfIndividual = adult2
// tree2.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual = adult1
// tree2.FirstChild.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual = kid1
// tree2.FirstChild.FirstChild.FirstChild = null
// tree2.FirstChild.FirstChild.SecondChild = null
// tree2.FirstChild.SecondChild = null
// tree2.SecondChild = null

Tree tree3 = tree2.PopOldest();

// tree3.SmurfIndividual = adult1
// tree3.FirstChild.SmurfIndividual = kid1
// tree3.FirstChild.FirstChild = null
// tree3.FirstChild.SecondChild = null
// tree3.SecondChild = null

Tree tree4 = tree3.PopOldest();

// tree3.SmurfIndividual = kid1
// tree3.FirstChild = null
// tree3.SecondChild = null

Tree tree5 = tree4.PopOldest();

// tree5 = null

This method uses a deep copy of the tree and modify the copy with PopOldest() to return the list of all SmurfIndividuals in the tree from oldest to youngest.
This method will be called only on Tree where the SmurfIndividual in every node is older than the SmurfIndividuals in the two children of this node.

Information
This sort is called the "Heap Sort". It uses a binary tree in which every node is greater than its child in case of max heap, or lesser than its child in case of min heap. Here, we use a max heap where the value of nodes are the age of the smurf.

Prototype(s)
public List<SmurfIndividual> GetOldestToYoungest() { }

Code example(s)
Elder elder1 = new Elder("Grandpa Smurf", 102, "Telling stories");
Adult adult1 = new Adult("WildSmurf", 23, "Explorer", 5);
Adult adult2 = new Adult("TrackerSmurf", 27, "Tracker", 13);
Kid kid1 = new Kid("DreamySmurf", 7, 68, 5);
Tree tree1 = new Tree(elder1, new Tree(adult1, new Tree(kid1)), new Tree(adult2));
List<SmurfIndividual> list = tree1.getOldestToYoungest();

// list.Count = 4
// list[0] = elder1
// list[1] = adult2
// list[2] = adult1
// list[3] = kid1
